17 "(b) A physician holding a child in temporary protective custody shall:
18 (1) Make reasonable and diligent efforts to inform the child's parents, guardian, or legal
19 custodian of the whereabouts of such child and the right to obtain an independent medical
20 evaluation or specialty consultation as provided for under Code Section 15-11-131.1;
21 (2) As soon as possible, make a report of the suspected abuse or neglect which caused
22 him or her to take temporary custody of the child and inform DFCS of the basis of his or
23 her determinations, including whether a physical examination was conducted and what
24 medical records were reviewed, and that such child has been held in temporary custody;
25 and
26 (3) Not later than 24 hours after such child is held in temporary custody:
27 (A) Contact a juvenile court intake officer, and inform such intake officer that such
28 child is in imminent danger to his or her life or health as a result of suspected abuse or
29 neglect; or
30 (B) Contact a law enforcement officer who shall take such child and promptly bring
31 such child before a juvenile court intake officer."
32 SECTION 2.
33 Said chapter is further amended in said article by adding a new Code section to read as
34 follows:
35 "15-11-131.1.
36 (a) As used in this Code section, the term 'specialty consultation' means a consultation with
37 a physician licensed to practice medicine in this state and board certified in the relevant
38 field or specialty, including radiology, genetics, orthopedics, and endocrinology, to
39 diagnose and treat certain unique health conditions, including rickets, Ehlers-Danlos
40 syndrome, osteogenesis imperfecta, vitamin D deficiency, or other medical conditions that
41 mimic the physical manifestations of child abuse or neglect or increase the risk of
42 misdiagnosis of child abuse or neglect.
